1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
Good day and welcome back to your Learn WordPress journey.

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:07,000
In this section we're going to dive into a fundamental aspect of WordPress,

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:11,000
understanding the difference between posts and pages.

4
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Here are the learning outcomes for this lesson.

5
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:18,000
We will learn to differentiate between posts and pages,

6
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:21,000
create a post and page, apply categories and tags to posts,

7
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:25,000
and create and edit a page in the Site Editor.

8
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:29,000
Before we jump into the specifics,

9
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:32,000
let's start with an overview.

10
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:34,000
In WordPress, both posts and pages are content types,

11
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:40,000
but they serve different purposes.

12
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:43,000
In short, posts are used for dynamic content, such as blog posts,

13
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:48,000
news articles, recipes, etc.

14
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:52,000
Whereas pages are static type content, like a contact page, for example.

15
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:58,000
Here we are in the WordPress Dashboard. To create a new post or page,

16
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:02,000
you can navigate to the posts or pages section on the left-hand menu.

17
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:08,000
And if you want to create a new post or page,

18
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:11,000
merely click on Add New Post or Add New Page.

19
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:15,000
Let's start with posts.

20
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:18,000
Posts are for dynamic, regularly updated content entries

21
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:23,000
that are displayed in reverse chronological order.

22
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:27,000
They are perfect for content that you regularly update,

23
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:31,000
such as blog articles,

24
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:35,000
news pages,

25
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:41,000
or even reviews.

26
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:46,000
Imagine you have a cooking blog,

27
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:49,000
and you want to share your latest recipe.

28
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:53,000
You would create a new post for this content.

29
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Now, as you can see in this example, I have already created two different posts,

30
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:01,000
and I've added categories and tags.

31
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:05,000
Categories and tags are essential for posts.

32
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:08,000
Categories are like the table of contents for your blog,

33
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:11,000
grouping similar posts together.

34
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:13,000
Tags, on the other hand, are more specific keywords

35
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:16,000
that describe the content in greater detail.

36
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:19,000
So for my food blog, I've created two categories already,

37
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:23,000
one called Mains and one called Breakfast,

38
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:26,000
and the tags describe more about the recipe.

39
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:29,000
So let's go ahead and create a new post.

40
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:34,000
A Chocolate Cake Recipe.

41
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:37,000
But please note, I've already created a category named Dessert

42
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:43,000
and two tags, namely Cakes and Cupcakes, and Chocolate.

43
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:50,000
So now we'll go ahead to all posts, and then click on Add New Post.

44
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,000
Firstly, I will add the title of the blog post,

45
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:00,000
and then the recipe.

46
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:07,000
Once I've added the recipe, I will open up the sidebar settings

47
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:12,000
and scroll down to categories and tags.

48
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:16,000
Then I will select the Dessert category,

49
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:23,000
and add the Chocolate and Caking Cupcakes tags.

50
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:31,000
Next, I will also add the post featured image,

51
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:35,000
or the post thumbnail, and select an image from my media library.

52
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:42,000
Next, we can decide to save this as a draft,

53
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:45,000
or if we scroll up in our sidebar settings,

54
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:49,000
we can click on the date next to publish,

55
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:52,000
and then decide to publish this now,

56
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:56,000
or schedule it to go live at a later stage.

57
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:00,000
I will go ahead and publish this now,

58
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:03,000
and then we can see what our posts look like on the front end.

59
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:08,000
Here we can see our three recipes on our blog page,

60
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:12,000
and we can also open up one of our individual recipes

61
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:16,000
to see the end result.

62
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:21,000
Now let's talk about pages.

63
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:23,000
Pages are static, timeless content that doesn't change frequently.

64
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:28,000
Examples include your site's Home page, a Services page,

65
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:32,000
an About page and a Contact page.

66
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:36,000
If you want to create a dedicated About Us section for your website,

67
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:40,000
you'd use a page.

68
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:43,000
Unlike posts, pages don't have categories or tags.

69
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:47,000
They are standalone pieces of content,

70
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:50,000
so let's go ahead and add a new page,

71
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,000
and call it "About",

72
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:58,000
and then add some content.

73
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
Once published, we can view it on the front end,

74
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:07,000
and you will also notice that the About page is now part of the navigation menu.

75
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:15,000
Did you know you can also create and edit pages in the Site Editor?

76
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,000
So let's make our way to Editor,

77
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:23,000
and this will take us into the Site Editor.

78
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:28,000
Then we can make our way to pages, and here, you are able to create a new page,

79
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:36,000
or you can edit an existing page.

80
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:41,000
The great thing about the Site Editor is that you can seamlessly move between pages,

81
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,000
styles, templates, patterns, etc.

82
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:57,000
And there we have it.

83
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:58,000
Remember, posts are for dynamic, regularly updated content,

84
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:03,000
while pages are for static timeless information.

